rnard Bate begins with Protestant missionaries' introduction of the sermonic genre and takes the reader through its local vernacularization. What originally began as a format of religious speech became an essential political infrastructure used to galvanize support for new social imaginaries, from Indian independence to Tamil nationalism. Completed by a team of Bate's colleagues, this ethnography marries linguistic anthropology to performance studies and political history, illuminating new geographies of belonging in the modern era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aLanguage and culturezSouth AsiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical oratoryxHistoryzSouth Asiay20th century. 0aPolitical oratoryzSouth AsiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectsxHistoryzSouth Asiay20th century. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszSouth AsiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTamil (Indic people)xPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aTamil languagexPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aIndia.  aModernity.  aOratory.  aPolitics.  aPublic Sphere.  aTamil.  aTextuality.1 aAnnamalai, E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnnamalai, E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCody, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCody, Francis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJayanth, Malarvizhi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaviraj, Sudipta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakassis, Constantine V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNakassis, Constantine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVenkatach